  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash arises from an assertion
in VFRange's constructor requiring that End (the exclusive upper bound of the
range) be a power of two. The loop vectorizer constructs a VFRange in
LoopVectorizationPlanner::buildVPlansWithVPRecipes using {VF, MaxVFTimes2}, where
MaxVFTimes2 = MaxVF * 2. In the observed failure, MaxVF = 10, so End = 20, which
violates the power-of-two constraint and triggers the assertion. All internal
logic in VPlan iteration assumes vectorization factors (VFs) are powers of two; a
non power-of-two VF corrupts those assumptions and causes the crash.\n\n2.
Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe minimized reproducer contains a simple loop with stride
3 induction and two memory accesses with different base indices, one at [0][iv]
and one at [8][iv], both i16. ScalarEvolution reports trip-dependent expressions
but nothing unusual. The first transformation site is the construction of
VFRange, which crashes before any IR mutation occurs. The presence of MaxVF = 10
in the debugger indicates that the cost model (computeFeasibleMaxVF /
getMaximizedVFForTarget) produced a non-power-of-two FixedVF, violating an
implicit invariant that all fixed VFs must be powers of two.\n\n3. Root Cause
Analysis:\nThe only path to a non power-of-two FixedVF is a missing normalization
step after selecting a candidate VF. getMaximizedVFForTarget itself enforces
power-of-two in its initial calculation (bit_floor) and when clamping to trip
count (bit_floor(MaxTripCount)), and its bandwidth expansion loop only enumerates
powers-of-two (doubling). However, a target hook (e.g. getMinimumVF) or future
extensions could return a non power-of-two value. Even without a target override,
the observed binary produced FixedVF=10, meaning some configuration produced a
MaxVF that escaped the power-of-two filtering (likely due to an unforeseen
target-specific interaction or an out-of-tree change). The planner blindly trusts
MaxVF and forms a VFRange whose End = MaxVF*2, leading to assertion failure when
MaxVF is not a power-of-two. The invariant is not revalidated before VFRange
construction.\n\nTherefore the loop vectorizer lacks a defensive normalization
step to enforce its requirement that FixedVF values are powers-of-two. This
causes instability when a target (or experimental option) produces a
non-conforming VF.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Points:\nEdit Point 1 (lines 3900-3905,
LoopVectorize.cpp): After assigning Result.FixedVF and Result.ScalableVF in
computeFeasibleMaxVF, insert normalization code to clamp any non-power-of-two VF
down to the nearest lower power-of-two (bit_floor). This preserves safety while
maintaining maximal safe VF semantics.\nChange:\nAfter:\n  if (auto MaxVF =
getMaximizedVFForTarget(...))\n    Result.FixedVF = MaxVF;\nAdd:\n  if
(Result.FixedVF && !isPowerOf2_32(Result.FixedVF.getKnownMinValue()))\n
Result.FixedVF =
ElementCount::getFixed(bit_floor(Result.FixedVF.getKnownMinValue()));\nSimilarly
after scalable assignment:\n  if (Result.ScalableVF &&
!isPowerOf2_32(Result.ScalableVF.getKnownMinValue()))\n    Result.ScalableVF =
ElementCount::getScalable(bit_floor(Result.ScalableVF.getKnownMinValue()));\n\nRa
tionale: Ensures all returned Fixed and Scalable (minimum counts) VFs uphold
power-of-two invariant regardless of target anomalies.\n\nEdit Point 2 (lines
9229-9233, LoopVectorize.cpp): In buildVPlansWithVPRecipes, before constructing
VFRange, add a defensive clamp for MaxVF used in MaxVFTimes2 and optionally
assert if unexpected. This is a secondary safeguard preventing future
non-normalized values causing crashes.\nAdd code after computing MaxVFTimes2:\n
if (MaxVF && !isPowerOf2_32(MaxVF.getKnownMinValue())) {\n    MaxVF =
ElementCount::get(MaxVF.isScalable() ? bit_floor(MaxVF.getKnownMinValue()) :
bit_floor(MaxVF.getKnownMinValue()), MaxVF.isScalable());\n    MaxVFTimes2 =
MaxVF * 2;\n  }\n  assert(isPowerOf2_32(MaxVF.getKnownMinValue()) && \"Expected
